   "id": "e1704de9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "2. The Normalization and Epsilon ($\\epsilon$):You added transforms.Normalize(mean=(0.1307,), std=(0.3081,)). This is standard best practice for training a PyTorch model! However, for adversarial attacks, this changes the mathematics of your perturbation bound ($\\epsilon$). If you normalize the data, your pixel values are no longer perfectly scaled between [0, 1]; they will have a mean of 0 and a variance of 1.The fix: When you configure your attacks in secml-torch later, you will just need to make sure the library knows about this normalization step so it calculates the attack bounds correctly. Keep it in your code, just be aware of it!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "id": "97b62405",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "trainset = torchvision.datasets.MNIST(\n",
    "    root= './data', \n",
